frameDefinitions: In this frame a Deformer deforms a Patient possibly against a Resistant_surface such that it undergoes a shape-change from its canonical or original shape into the Configuration, a new shape.
A Speaker expresses through language his wish to get the Addressee to act.
An Agent manipulates a linear entity (the Rope) to form a Knot.
The words in this frame have to do with people and the personal Relationships they are or can be a part of.
An Agent creates a Knot (possibly in a Place and/or with an Instrument).'

These words describe the recovery or healing of a Patient from an Affliction without reference to the influence of any Treatment or Healer (see the Cure frame).  '' 'My injuries had not yet completely healed.'
frameExamples: Ellen <t>crumpled</t> the paper into a ball.
You think I <t>talked</t> Peter into giving me those earrings, don't you?
Harry <t>tied</t> the rope into a slipknot.
And of course that drippy <t><fex name='Partner_1'>boyfriend</fex></t> of hers backed her up.
Loretta <t>ties</t> the most beautiful bowline I've ever seen.
My injuries had not yet completely <t>healed</t>.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Deformer</fen> is the one who does the reshaping.
The <fen>Patient</fen> is the entity acted on and that undergoes a change.
The <fen>Cause</fen> is an animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that produces an effect. Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of <fen>Cause</fen>s.
A state that holds of the <fen>Patient</fen> or a relation that holds among the constituent parts of the <fen>Patient</fen> as a result of the arranging action.
The role <fen>Time</fen> identifies when the <fen>Deformer</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the <fen>Deformer</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Patient</fen>.
The <fen>Speaker</fen> intends through the use of language to get another person to act.
The wish for action on the <fen>Addressee</fen>'s part  that the <fen>Speaker</fen> expresses.
The person that the Speaker seeks to influence to act.
The location where the <fen>Speaker</fen> talks the <fen>Addressee</fen> into performing the <fen>Content</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the sentient being who manipulates the <fen>Rope</fen>.
The basically linear object which is manipulated by the <fen>Agent</fen> to produce a <fen>Knot</fen>.
The stable configuration of a <fen>Rope</fen> which results from tying.
When the manipulation of the <fen>Rope</fen> takes place.
Where the manipulation of the <fen>Rope</fen> takes place.
That partner in the <fen>Relationship</fen> who is realized as the subject of verbs in active form sentences, or of adjectives in predicative uses.
That partner in the <fen>Relationship</fen> who is not expressed as the external argument.
The joint construal of both <fen>Partners</fen> in the <fen>Relationship</fen>.
The Agent is the person performing the intentional act.
The stable configuration of a String which results from tying.
When the event occurs.
Where the event takes place.
The    Patient may either be expressed as the External Argument or, as in Health.Cure, may occur as the possessor of the Affliction (an example of role conflation):
This role is the injury, pain or disease experienced by the Patient.  Affliction occurs either as an External Argument of verbs or as a PP Complement of nouns or verbs:
Where Body Part is expressed as a separate constituent (rather than in phrases such as <ment>the wound on Pat's arm</ment>), it occurs as an External Argument:
The time at which the recovery takes place.
The location where the recovery takes place.
